## MongoDB Document Model & Schema Design

### Document Structure
```javascript
{
  "_id": ObjectId("507f1f77bcf86cd799439011"),
  "name": "John",
  "address": {
    "street": "123 Main St",
    "city": "NYC"
  },
  "hobbies": ["reading", "gaming"]
}
```

### Schema Flexibility
- No predefined schema (schemaless)
- Add/remove fields freely
- Documents can differ
- Trade-off: Less type safety

### Embed vs Reference

**Embed** (Subdocument):
```javascript
// Address with user always
db.users.insertOne({
  name: "John",
  address: { street: "123", city: "NYC" }
});
```
Benefits: Single query, atomic, better performance

**Reference** (Separate collection):
```javascript
// Comments accessed separately
db.users.insertOne({
  name: "John",
  comment_ids: [ObjectId(), ObjectId()]
});
```
Benefits: Data reuse, smaller docs, update flexibility

### Design Patterns

**One-to-One**: Embed (profile in user)
**One-to-Many (small)**: Embed (comments in post)
**One-to-Many (large)**: Reference (addresses by user)
**Many-to-Many**: Reference both ways

### Best Practices
- Keep docs < 16 MB limit
- Embed frequently accessed data
- Reference rarely accessed or frequently updated
- Denormalize for read performance
- Validate with JSON Schema

### Validation
```javascript
db.createCollection("users", {
  validator: {
    $jsonSchema: {
      required: ["name", "email"],
      properties: {
        name: { bsonType: "string" },
        email: { bsonType: "string", pattern: "^[a-z0-9._%+-]+@[a-z0-9.-]+\\.[a-z]{2,}$" }
      }
    }
  }
});
```

## Indexing & Query Optimization in MongoDB

### Index Types

**Single Field**:
```javascript
db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 });
db.users.find({ email: "john@example.com" });  // Uses index
```

**Compound**:
```javascript
db.orders.createIndex({ user_id: 1, created_at: -1 });
db.orders.find({ user_id: 1, created_at: { $gte: date } });  // Uses index
```

**Text**:
```javascript
db.articles.createIndex({ title: "text", body: "text" });
db.articles.find({ $text: { $search: "MongoDB" } });
```

**Geospatial**:
```javascript
db.locations.createIndex({ coordinates: "2dsphere" });
db.locations.find({
  coordinates: { $near: { type: "Point", coordinates: [-74, 40] }, $maxDistance: 5000 }
});
```

**TTL** (Auto-expire):
```javascript
db.sessions.createIndex({ createdAt: 1 }, { expireAfterSeconds: 3600 });
```

### ESR Rule: Equality → Sort → Range
```javascript
// For: WHERE a=1, b>10 ORDER BY c DESC
db.col.createIndex({ a: 1, c: -1, b: 1 });
//                  ├─ Equality (a)
//                  ├─ Sort (c)
//                  └─ Range (b)
```

### Query Analysis
```javascript
db.users.find({ email: "john@example.com" }).explain("executionStats");
// Shows: INDEX_SCAN (good) vs COLLSCAN (bad)
// documentExamined: 1 (good) vs 1000 (bad)
```

### Anti-patterns
- ❌ Low-cardinality indexes
- ❌ Not using explain()
- ❌ Duplicate indexes
- ❌ Over-indexing (slows writes)
- ✅ Frequently queried fields
- ✅ Compound for multi-field
- ✅ Monitor slow queries

## Transactions & ACID Guarantees in MongoDB

### Multi-Document Transactions (4.0+)
```javascript
session = db.getMongo().startSession();
session.startTransaction();

try {
  db.accounts.updateOne(
    { account_id: "A" },
    { $inc: { balance: -100 } },
    { session: session }
  );

  db.accounts.updateOne(
    { account_id: "B" },
    { $inc: { balance: +100 } },
    { session: session }
  );

  session.commitTransaction();
} catch (e) {
  session.abortTransaction();
  throw e;
}
```

### Single-Document ACID
```javascript
// Atomic even for multiple operations
db.orders.updateOne(
  { _id: 1 },
  {
    $set: { status: "paid" },
    $push: { payments: { amount: 100, date: new Date() } }
  }
  // All-or-nothing
);
```

### Isolation: Snapshot
- Reads own writes
- Sees snapshot at transaction start
- No dirty reads, lost updates, phantom reads

### Read Concern Levels
```javascript
// local: Read from primary (may rollback)
db.collection.find().readConcern("local");

// majority: Majority-committed (no rollback)
db.collection.find().readConcern("majority");

// linearizable: Latest committed
db.collection.find().readConcern("linearizable");
```

### Transaction Limits
- Max 16 MB (same as document)
- Max 1000 operations
- No schema changes in transaction
- Limited shard support (4.2+)

### When to Use
✅ Multi-step atomicity needed
✅ Cross-collection consistency
✅ Financial/critical ops

❌ High-volume inserts (bulk ops better)
❌ Long-running (timeout risk)
❌ Sharded heavy contention

### Performance Impact
- 10% latency increase typical
- Choose isolation carefully
- Default (snapshot) fine for most apps

